body:
## What problem does this solve or what need does it fill?

`Mut<T>` has an escape hatch in the form of `bypass_change_detection()`, which allows any component-based workflow to "manually" handle change detection tagging.

For assets, they're stored into an `Assets<T>` which has a single mutable accessor: `get_mut()`. That accessor unconditionally send an `AssetEvent::Modified` when called. There's no possible escape hatch, even using `Mut` or `ResMut`, because that feature is baked into the underlying mutable access a level under `Mut` and `ResMut`.

This is problematic in particular for the end goal of erasing the differences of component vs. asset (for a function which doesn't care where the target object is coming from) and trying to obtain a `Mut<A: Asset>` from a `Mut<Assets<A>>` and a `Handle<A>`. You can call `reborrow()` to go from `ResMut<Assets<A>>` to `Mut<Assets<A>>`, and then `map_unchanged()` to go from `Mut<Assets<A>>` to `Mut<A>`, but unfortunately during the latter call you need to call `Assets::get_mut()` and that will send a mutation event.

```rust
fn sys(assets: ResMut<Assets<A>>, handle: Handle<A>) -> Mut<A> {
  let mut_assets: Mut<Assets<A>> = assets.reborrow();
  let mut_asset: Mut<A> = mut_assets.map_unchanged(|a| a.get_mut(handle)); // game over; get_mut() already sent an event
  mut_asset
}
```

## What solution would you like?

```rust
impl<A: Asset> Assets<A> {
  fn bypass_change_detection(&mut self, id: impl Into<AssetId<A>>) -> Option<&mut A> {
    // exactly the same as get_mut(), without sending any AssetEvent::Modified
  }
}
```

## What alternative(s) have you considered?

At the minute I add my own indirection `Targetable` trait _on top of_ `Mut<T>`, so that I can hold either the `Mut<C: Component>`, or the `Mut<Assets<A>>` _and_ the associated `Handle<A>`. This is impractical and feels silly.

## Additional context

https://github.com/djeedai/bevy_tweening/blob/d484c5a6c2d62a5fb5526ab3dc0720d533080668/src/tweenable.rs#L196-L205
